# ABA CLI syntax

## The `-d` / `--dir` flag is required to run a target in a subdirectory

```bash
# CORRECT — run the "save" target inside the mirror/ directory
aba -d mirror save
aba -d mirror install
aba -d mirror load
aba -d compact1 install

# WRONG — "aba mirror save" does NOT mean "save inside mirror/"
# "aba mirror" means "create a new mirror directory called mirror"
aba mirror save        # WRONG
aba mirror install     # WRONG
aba compact1 install   # WRONG
```

## Why this matters

`aba <name>` creates a new named resource (mirror or cluster directory).
`aba -d <dir> <target>` runs a make target inside an existing directory.

These are completely different operations. Confusing them produces invalid commands.

## Quick reference

| Intent | Correct | Wrong |
|--------|---------|-------|
| Save images | `aba -d mirror save` | `aba mirror save` |
| Install registry | `aba -d mirror install` | `aba mirror install` |
| Load images | `aba -d mirror load` | `aba mirror load` |
| Install cluster | `aba -d mycluster install` | `aba mycluster install` |
| Create a mirror dir | `aba mirror` | (this one IS correct) |
| Create a cluster dir | `aba sno --name foo` | (this one IS correct) |
